The perturbative calculation is also not accurate enough for another reason, which we illustrate by expressing the calculation diagrammatically \cite{Wong8}. \Fref{fig:diagram_H} expresses the full search Hamiltonian $H$, and \fref{fig:diagram_H0} expresses its leading-order terms $H^{(0)}$. When $\gamma = 1/3n$, ${\left| {d_0} \right\rangle}$ and ${\left| {d_3} \right\rangle}$ are degenerate in \fref{fig:diagram_H0} since they have self-loops of the same weight. With the perturbation $H^{(1)}$, we get \fref{fig:diagram_H0H1}, which restores the missing edges. But since there is no edge connecting ${\left| {d_0} \right\rangle}$ and ${\left| {d_3} \right\rangle}$, these states do not mix; the perturbed eigenstates roughly remain ${\left| {d_0} \right\rangle}$ and ${\left| {d_3} \right\rangle}$, not a combination of the two, and so probability does not flow between the vertices.

